The limit evaluates to the form 0/0,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{x^2-3x-4}{\sqrt{x}-2} &=\frac{4^2-3(4)-4}{\sqrt{4}-2}\\
&= \frac{16-12-4}{2-2}\\
&= \frac{0}{0}\end{align*}

which is undefined. However, notice that in the denominator we can get
rid of the square root by multiplying top and bottom by the conjugate

\begin{align*}\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{x^2-3x-4}{\sqrt{x}-2}\cdot \frac{\sqrt{x}+2}{\sqrt{x}+2}=\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{(x^2-3x-4)(\sqrt{x}+2)}{x-4}.\end{align*}

Now notice that the quadratic polynomial on the top can factor,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x^2-3x-4=(x-4)(x+1)\end{align*}

and therefore

\begin{align*}
&\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{(x^2-3x-4)(\sqrt{x}+2)}{x-4}\\
&=\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{(x-4)(x+1))(\sqrt{x}+2)}{x-4}\\
&=\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} (x+1)(\sqrt{x}+2)\\
&=20.\end{align*}

Therefore

\begin{align*}\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{x^2-3x-4}{\sqrt{x}-2} =\frac{4^2-3(4)-4}{\sqrt{4}-2}=20.\end{align*}

The limit evaluates to the form 0/0,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{x^2-3x-4}{\sqrt{x}-2} &=\frac{4^2-3(4)-4}{\sqrt{4}-2}\\
&= \frac{16-12-4}{2-2}\\
&= \frac{0}{0}\end{align*}

which is undefined. 0/0 is a form for which we can apply l'Hospital's
rule (if you know it):

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{x^2-3x-4}{\sqrt{x}-2} &=\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{\frac{d}{dx}\Big(x^2-3x-4\Big)}{\frac{d}{dx}\Big(\sqrt{x}-2\Big)} \\
&=\lim_{x\rightarrow 4} \frac{2x-3}{\frac{1}{2}x^{-1/2}} \\ 
&= \frac{5}{\frac{1}{2}4^{-1/2}} \\ 
&= \frac{5}{1/4} \\ 
&= 20\end{align*}
